{
  "text": "2+ -Dependent Folding Transitions The contribution of each tertiary interaction to the folding free energy of the Azoarcus ribozyme was measured by titrating the WT and mutant ribozymes with Mg 2+ (Figure 3 ). In general, stable RNA tertiary structures require less Mg 2+ to form, and the steepness of the folding transition correlates with the free energy gap between the unfolded and folded states (see Experimental Procedures) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The tolerance of the Azoarcus ribozyme toward destabilizing mutations validated our energy perturbation approach, and allowed us to measure the complete free energy landscape for folding and coupling energies without having to assume that mutations ablate a tertiary interaction motif. The free energy change associated with forming the native state (DG I/N ) was obtained from the increase in pre-steady-state ribozyme activity with Mg 2+ ( Figures 3A and S3 ). The free energy change between U and I C (DG U/I ) was obtained from the decrease in R g 2 measured by SAXS, under the same conditions as the activity assays ( Figures 3B and S3 ). Using previously validated folding models [CITATION_3] to extract populations of U, I C , and N ( Figures 3C and 3D ), free energies for each folding transition were evaluated at 0.8 mM Mg 2+ for I C , 5 mM Mg 2+ for N [CITATION_4] . These reference conditions correspond to 90% saturation of each transition, and were chosen to be near the midpoint of each transition where the assumptions underlying the free energy calculations are most valid . Full details of the analysis are given in Experimental Procedures, Figure S3 , and Table S2 .",
